The result means that investments in children, and therefore the quality of children, increase as longevity increases in the equilibrium in which investments are purchased in the market. Intuitively, this happens here since increases in longevity reduce the shadow cost of investments in children, because of a lowered fertility rate, and expand the budget constraint (higher lifetime income of both members of the family). When τ increases, n falls and y increases more than proportionately (

